Should 0 be a valid value for ``patience``? It looks like a reasonable value for expressing "no patience".

* If yes, I think it should be equivalent to ``patience == 1``: the training should be stopped at the end of the first epoch without improvement. 
* if no, maybe it's the case to add a check ``patience > 0`` in the constructor.

Currently, for ``patience == 0``, the stop condition is never met because in ``Trainer._should_stop_early``:
```
if self._validation_metric_decreases:
    return min(metric_history[-self._patience:]) > min(metric_history)
else:
    return max(metric_history[-self._patience:]) < max(metric_history)
```
 ``metric_history[-0:] == metric_history`` so the inequality between their min/max is always false.

# String.IndexOf behaviour differs from .NET Standard, but only on Linux

```
using System;

namespace Bug
{
  public class Program
  {
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
      string lSOH1 = Convert.ToChar((byte)1).ToString();
      Console.WriteLine(lSOH1);
      var lLine1 = string.Format("123{0}", lSOH1);
      Console.WriteLine(lLine1);
      Console.WriteLine(lLine1.IndexOf(lSOH1)); // Should print "3"
    }
  }
}
```

If I build and run this code in Visual Studio 2017 on Windows 7 the output of the last line is, as expected, "3". However if I run the built code on Centos 7 with dotnet core 2 (rh-dotnet20-2.0-6.el7), the output is "0". Running the same code under mono works fine. Building the code using dotnet itself on Centos makes no difference to the behaviour.

